    {
      "question": "Two triangles $\\triangle ABC$ and $\\triangle DEF$ are similar. If $Area(\\triangle ABC) = 64$ $cm^2$ and $Area(\\triangle DEF) = 121$ $cm^2$, and $EF = 11$ $cm$, find the length of $BC$.",
      "answer": "$8$ $cm$",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Use the theorem: The ratio of areas of two similar triangles is equal to the square of the ratio of their corresponding sides.",
          "Set up the equation $\\frac{Area(\\triangle ABC)}{Area(\\triangle DEF)} = (\\frac{BC}{EF})^2$ and solve for $BC$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$\\frac{64}{121} = (\\frac{BC}{11})^2 \\Rightarrow \\sqrt{\\frac{64}{121}} = \\frac{BC}{11} \\Rightarrow \\frac{8}{11} = \\frac{BC}{11} \\Rightarrow BC = 8$ $cm$"
      },
